Project Report

LCJJ

Author

Charlie Lovett, Jacob Muriel, Lainey Neild, and Jack Troxel

Published

May 23, 2023

Abstract
This project focuses on the development of a model to predict salaries in STEM fields. In this project, the optimization metric used was Mean Absolute Error. An MAE on testing data of ~47,000 was achieved using the following models and ensembling techniques- Ridge, Lasso, Random Forest, AdaBoost, Gradient Boosting, and XGBoost. Based on this model, stakeholders including students and employers can more accurately predict salaries to correctly value work and avoid overcompensating employees.

1 Background / Motivation

All four of us are current college students that will soon be entering the professional world. Many of us are planning to pursue careers in various STEM fields such as software development or data science. With this in mind, we wanted to create a model that can help to predict the salaries of the people that work in these fields. Through this project, we wanted to develop a model that we could one day use to predict what our salaries should be.

2 Problem statement

Through this project, we will attempt to predict the salaries for employees that work in STEM fields. As we are predicting salaries, the response observed in this project is a continuous variableâtheir annunal salary in USD. We will assess our model accuracy using MAE. We have selected this metric instead of RMSE as there is no inherit risk or disadvantage in incorrectly predicting observations by a large margin.

3 Data sources

We will be using a data source comprised of salary data for employees in STEM fields. This dataset was found on Kaggle and contains data scraped from a salary collecting website (levels.fyi). The data can be found here.

The response in this problem is totalyearlycompensation. Some of the predictors include company, title, yearsofexperience, yearsatcompany, location, Education, Race, and Gender.

There are ~21,000 observations in our dataset. There are 10 total predictors comprised of 2 continuous and 8 categorical predictors.

4 Stakeholders

The dataset our group has chosen to analyze investigates the compensation for various STEM roles at companies. Many groups of people could benefit from this analysis. Firstly, students pursuing a career in STEM would definitely be interested in this data. Although compensation does not drive most studentâs professional path, it certainly is a factor that holds weight. Secondly, colleges and universities would benefit from our groupâs analysis. By understanding which roles are in the highest demand in our society, they may place more emphasis on prioritizing resources and professors in those academic areas. Thirdly, employees would be interested in our findings to ensure that their compensation is fair relative to industry standards, giving them the opportunity to negotiate for higher pay. Fourthly, in the same way our analysis could benefit employees, employers would benefit as they could see how their compensation packages compare to their competitorâs compensation packages allowing them to understand better how they are attracting talent in these fields and how to make the open positions more attractive to prospective employees.

5.1.2 Data Cleaning:

We droped: * location and cityid since we used dmaid to account for location instead of the location column since it was more generalized and a bit broader. * Race and Education - these already existed as dummy variable columns in the dataframe * Timestampd, basesalary, stockgrantvalue, otherdetails, rowNumber, bonus since we did not see these columns as contibuting to the current salary

Other changes: * We converting the dmaid to a string since the value of a âzipcodeâ cannot be considered as a numerical value. * We dropped all values where gender, race, or education were null * We cleaned all values that were âmessyâ through case conversion, dropping certain characters (spaces, commas, periods, etc.)

See the code below:

# Data Cleaning
# use dmaid for location predictor
data_cleaned = data.drop(columns = ["location", "timestamp", "basesalary", "stockgrantvalue", "otherdetails", "rowNumber", "bonus", "cityid"])
data_cleaned = data_cleaned.loc[data_cleaned.gender.notnull() & data_cleaned.Race.notnull() & data_cleaned.Education.notnull()]
data_cleaned = data_cleaned.drop(columns = ["Race", "Education"]) # alreadyy listed as dummy vars
data_cleaned.company = data_cleaned.company.str.lower()
data_cleaned.company = data_cleaned.company.str.replace(" ", "")
data_cleaned.company = data_cleaned.company.str.replace("-", "")
data_cleaned.company = data_cleaned.company.str.replace(",", "")
data_cleaned.company = data_cleaned.company.str.replace(".", "")
data_cleaned['dmaid'] = data_cleaned['dmaid'].astype(str)

The following columns were categoricalâ company, tag, title, level, dmaid. To account for the extremely high level of value counts, we selected the top 10 value counts from compnay, tag, title, and level. We could cinfidently do this since many of these values had value counts less than 10. In other words, if there was an extremely low value count in this column, we knew it would not contribute to the test accuracy of our model. We did keep many of the dmaid values though since including them all (above a very low threshold) was only 46 total new predictors.

top_cmp_lst = data_cleaned.company.value_counts().index.to_list()[:10]

7 Approach

As we showed in the data cleaning and preparation section, we created dummy variables for a few of the categorical predictors. Therefore, our training dataset had 107 predictors. With this large of a set of predictors, we knew that any model that fit the data well would drop several unimportant predictors. This is why we chose to use Lasso and Ridge regression. Lasso and Ridge effectively minimize the effect of unimportant predictors through L1 and L2 regularization. We used random forests because of its power to reduce variance, and we tried several boosting methods to enhance the model.

We optimized MAE for this prediction problem because there is no inherent risk in predicting a salary incorrectly. RMSE as a metric to optimize makes sense when an inaccurate prediction is dangerous, but this is not an issue when predicting STEM salaries.

Our problem did have some solutions in Kaggle. We used the best solutions to guide our approach to this problem: the best solution we found used random forests and boosting methods to optimize MAE, so we included these models in our problem. Another existing solution used a linear model and their MAE was extremely high (~1.9 trillion). This made it clear to us that there may have been some key outliers in our data that made it difficult for linear models to predict salary.

We did not use any additional code repositories.

8 Developing the model: Hyperparameter tuning

8.1 Lasso & Ridge

By Charlie Lovett

The process for developing Lasso and Ridge models is simple because there is only one hyperparameter to tune for each: the regularization constant alpha. Both processes were nearly identical:

I began by standardizing the predictors. This is important when using Lasso and Ridge because the algorithms penalize the coefficients of the predictors. If the predictors arenât on the same scale, the penalization would be dominated by those that are on a larger scale.

For each model, I used a coarse search for alpha and a fine search for alpha. For Lasso, these ranges were \(10**np.linspace(2,-3,50)*0.1\) and \(10**np.linspace(-3,-2,100)\), respectively. For Ridge, these ranges were \(10**np.linspace(10,-2,200)*0.5\) and \(10**np.linspace(1.7,2.06,200)\), respectively.

The resulting alpha for Lasso was 0.001 and the alpha for Ridge was 85.06. With these values, the results were as follows:

Lasso Final MAE: â55359.5

Ridge Final MAE: 55394.6

8.2 Random Forest

By Lainey Neild

I started by typing to optimize n_estimators by plotting the r-squared values for both test data and out of bag, looking to see where the r-squared stopped increasing and began to plateau. I repeated this process for MAE as well. The plots were not extremely helpful as they did not show a dramatic inclineâhowever, in the R-squared plot, there is a slight increase and then a plateau at around 375 trees. As seen in both graphs, at 375 trees, the MAR or R-squared is either at max or the line was relatively constant throughout. This allowed me to set n_estimators at 375 throughout the hyperparameter tuning.

Next, I completed many iterative loops through arbitrarily set parameters. I started with the parameters from the stat303 notes for max_depth, max_leaf_nodes, and max_features and then continuously adjusted the ranges. After ~5 of these loops, I got a good sense of the range of each hyperparameter, which allowed me to conduct more effective Grid Searches with 5 folds.

My final iteration used this pramater grid:

n_estimators: [375], max_depth: [23, 24, 25, 26, 27], max_leaf_nodes:[3100, 3250, 3400], max_features: [20]

I got the following optimal paramters:

max_depth=25 max_leaf_nodes=3100

In this iteraction, I set max_features to 20 since I had already narrowed that hyperparamtereâs range enough through the previous iterations. I also was able to decide that max_depth and max_leaf_nodes had a narrow enoguh range and I could stop these wider parameter searches and move onto grid searches. I came to this conclusions since max_depth return the value in the middle of itâs range of a and although max_leaf_nodes return the lower bound of its range, I had already throughoutly tested max_leaf_nodes less than 3100.

Ultimately, I completed 2 GridSearchCV to optimize all the hyperparameters. The first extended the many iterations I took over a broad sense of each hyperparameter. This first GridSearch further narrowed the range, and then I conducted one more to finalize my hyperparameter values.

My final GridSearch used the followinf parameters:

n_estimators: [375], max_depth: [25, 26, 27, 28, 29], max_leaf_nodes:[32500, 3500, 3750], max_features: [18, 20, 22]

Althoguh this range seems quite narrow, I had already done sufficient range testing so I felt confident in the values I selected.

The final model: n_estimators=375 max_leaf_nodes=3500 max_depth=25 max_features=22

Final MAE: $48,520

8.3 AdaBoost

By Jacob Muriel

Before I started tuning the hyperparameters, I plotted a cross validated MAE for each value of the hyperparameters against the value itself, to get a better sense of how I should approach the hyperparemeter space. I then used those graphs to determine what hyperparemeter values I should put in my grid for the GridSearchCV. I got the resuld from the gridsearch, and decided to manually tune some of the values against a splitted version of the training data. Then, I included a final grid search once I had a better sense of the hyperparameter values that worked best.

Initial AdaBoost Search: - grid[ân_estimatorsâ] = [200] - grid[âmax_depthâ] = [4, 8, 12, 16, 20, 24] - grid[âlearning_rateâ] = [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1]

Final AdaBoost Search: - grid[ân_estimatorsâ] = [200] - grid[âmax_depthâ] = [14, 18, 20] - grid[âlearning_rateâ] = [0.05, 0.075, 0.1, 0.125, 1.15]

AdaBoost Optimal Hyperparameters: - n_estimators = 200 - max_depth = 18 - n_estimators = 0.005

8.4 Gradient Boosting & XGBoost

By Jack Troxel

I used extremely similar processes to tune both Gradient Boosting and XGBoost. For both, I started with an extremely coarse gridsearch using RandomizedSearchCV based on the results of an exploration into each hyperparameter value versus the corresponding cross validation MAE. After that, I conducted I finer search using GridSearchCV. I continued to narrow in on finer and finer parameters until I found that the optimal parameters from these searches were actually increasing MAE on test data (due to overfitting). The searches that I conducted and the results that I achieved are seen below. As seen, I did not include n_estimators in any of my searches. Instead, I tuned n_estimators individually after deciding upon the other optimal hyperparameters.

Initial Gradient Boosting Search (RandomizedSearchCV): - grid[âlearning_rateâ] = [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01,0.1, 1.0] - grid[âmax_depthâ] = [5,6,7,8,9,10,11,12] - grid[âsubsampleâ] = [0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1]

Gradient Boosting Optimal Hyperparameters (after multiple rounds of finer tuning): - learning_rate = 0.1 - subsample = 0.75 - max_depth = 6 - n_estimators = 450

Gradient Boosting MAE on Test Data: 47,579

Initial XGBoost Search (RandomizedSearchCV): - grid[âmax_depthâ] = [3,4,5,6,7,8], - grid[âlearning_rateâ] = [0.1,0.2,0.3], - grid[âreg_lambdaâ] = [2, 10], - grid[âgammaâ] = [0, 10], - grid[âsubsampleâ] = [0.25,0.5,0.75,1]

XGBoost Optimal Hyperparameters (after multiple rounds of finer tuning): - max_depth = 6 - learning_rate = 0.08 - reg_lambda = 10 - gamma = 0 - subsample = 0.75 - n_estimators = 450

XGBoost MAE on Test Data: 47,440

10 Limitations of the model with regard to prediction

We are fairly confident in our chosen hyperparameters. While we did have a large dataset with a large amount of dummy variables, we still were able to perform effective grid searches to gauge the hyperparameter space with regards to our modelâs accuracy. That said, we obviously did not check every single combination of hyperparameters so it is definitely possible that there are better selections, and given some more time and computational power we likely could have achieved marginally better results. Additionally, it should not be too difficult for the stakeholders to collect relevant data relating to the predictors in the model. Individual students and employees should be aware of their own identities and the characteristics of their jobs (or prospective jobs) which is all they would need to use the model, and employers should have all the same information on their own employees to be used in the same way. It might be a bit more difficult for universities to track where their students typically work after studying or where their current students are likely to go, though they probably do have some of the relevant information on hand. The model may become obsolete by the year, in which case it could simply be updated by being trained on a new dataset with updated salaries and other relevant information. Once itâs updated, stakeholders should be able to use it right away to decide how to proceed with their future.

11 Conclusions and Recommendations to stakeholder(s)

Based on the results of our model, we are beyond satisfied in our ability to predict salaries for employees in STEM fields. Our modelâs MAE is significantly lower than that of the intercept only model and is also significanly lower than the initial standard deviation of the response variable, and both of those indicate that our model is performing significanly better than merely predicting the mean. Additionally, our stakeholders should be able to use our model to help in the following ways. Students pursuing a career in STEM can look at their own identities and weigh those with other potential aspects (company, what title they would have, etc.) to help them decide where they might want to work. Universities are likely aware of where their students typically go after studying, and they can use this information in tendem with our model to help them decide how to allocate their resources in a way that would set their students up for the most success (financially, at least). Employees can also look at their own identities and other aspects of their job to gauge whether they are being fairly compensated, and can use this information to decide whether they want to fight for a higher compensation of even try to go to another company. Lastly, employers can use the model in a similar way to see whether they are paying their employees too much, and can use it as a reasonable basis for denying some people higher compensations. That said, the stakeholders should probably be aware of a limitation that has to do with our model. Because of the large variety of results within the categorical predictors, we had to group and convert some variable names to âotherâ so reduce the computational complexity of our model, and thus not all companies, locations, and titles are distinctly addressed in this model. Additionally, our model should likely be updated every year (with a new dataset containing data from salaries and demographics from the most recent year) to account for overarching shifts in the industryâs salaries.
